1
00:02:04,708 --> 00:02:08,461
<i>NARRATOR".
In the year of Our Lord 1598,</i>

2
00:02:08,628 --> 00:02:12,799
<i>five trader warships left
the Dutch city of Rotterdam</i>

3
00:02:12,966 --> 00:02:15,593
<i>as the first expeditionary force
ever sent</i>

4
00:02:15,760 --> 00:02:19,431
<i>to ravage and plunder
Spanish and Portuguese possessions</i>

5
00:02:19,597 --> 00:02:22,225
<i>in the recently discovered
New World.</i>

6
00:02:22,392 --> 00:02:25,145
<i>Protestant Holland had been
at war with Catholic Spain</i>

7
00:02:25,311 --> 00:02:26,855
<i>for more than 4O years,</i>

8
00:02:27,021 --> 00:02:29,357
<i>with England her only ally
in the struggle.</i>

9
00:02:29,524 --> 00:02:32,736
<i>The Spanish had discovered
the vast riches of the Americas</i>

10
00:02:32,902 --> 00:02:38,742
<i>and, legend had it, the even greater
riches of mysterious Cathay.</i>

11
00:02:38,908 --> 00:02:43,371
<i>Both Holland and England were
determined to share in this wealth.</i>

12
00:02:43,538 --> 00:02:46,541
<i>Only one Dutch ship
survived the violent storms</i>

13
00:02:46,708 --> 00:02:48,251
<i>and icy seas of Cape Horn,</i>

14
00:02:48,418 --> 00:02:52,422
<i>to breach the enemy's secret
of the Straits of Magellan</i>

15
00:02:52,589 --> 00:02:56,384
<i>and finally
sail into American waters:</i>

16
00:02:56,551 --> 00:02:59,220
the Erasmus.

17
00:03:01,765 --> 00:03:04,976
<i>Under the command
of Pilot-Major John Blackthorne,</i>

18
00:03:05,143 --> 00:03:08,521
<i>with only 28 men
of his Dutch crew still alive,</i>

19
00:03:08,688 --> 00:03:12,734
<i>the Erasmus
ventured into the Pacific.</i>

20
00:03:21,951 --> 00:03:26,831
<i>There, pursued and outnumbered
by Spanish fleets, her retreat cut off,</i>

21
00:03:26,998 --> 00:03:31,920
<i>this ship turned westward
and fled alone...into the unknown.</i>

22
00:03:36,132 --> 00:03:39,636
<i>Now, almost two years
outward bound from home,</i>

23
00:03:39,803 --> 00:03:43,348
<i>133 days from her last landfall...</i>

24
00:03:43,515 --> 00:03:46,684
[THUNDER CRASHING]

25
00:04:07,580 --> 00:04:09,999
Go below, pilot. I take this watch.

26
00:04:10,166 --> 00:04:12,585
- Where's the mate?
- Dead.

27
00:04:12,752 --> 00:04:16,422
There's the stink of death, pilot.

28
00:04:16,589 --> 00:04:21,052
- What's the course?
- Wherever the wind takes us!

29
00:04:21,219 --> 00:04:24,389
And where's the landfall
you promised?

30
00:04:24,556 --> 00:04:26,349
Where's the Japans?

31
00:04:26,516 --> 00:04:29,769
- Ahead!
- Ahead...

32
00:04:29,936 --> 00:04:31,938
Always ahead!

33
00:04:33,690 --> 00:04:35,859
Blessed Jesus...

34
00:04:36,025 --> 00:04:39,445
Damn the day I left Holland!

35
00:04:51,082 --> 00:04:55,003
- Get aloft, Maetsukker.
- No, I'm near death, pilot.

36
00:04:55,169 --> 00:04:57,171
I'm sick. The scurvy's taken me.

37
00:04:57,338 --> 00:05:02,343
Get aloft and stay there till you're dead
or we make landfall!

38
00:05:06,347 --> 00:05:08,683
How are you feeling, Johann?

39
00:05:08,850 --> 00:05:12,770
Good enough, pilot.
Perhaps I'll live.

40
00:05:13,938 --> 00:05:17,400
Most men your age are already dead,
so you're ahead of us.

41
00:05:17,567 --> 00:05:21,112
It's the saintly life I've led.
That and the brandy--

42
00:05:21,279 --> 00:05:22,906
[GROANS]

43
00:05:29,078 --> 00:05:31,873
The boatswain's dead, pilot.

44
00:05:36,586 --> 00:05:40,006
Get the body aloft.
You and Roper and Croocq.

45
00:05:40,798 --> 00:05:43,426
Johann, take the dawn watch.

46
00:05:43,593 --> 00:05:47,263
- Ginsel, you're bow lookout.
- Right.

47
00:06:08,493 --> 00:06:10,495
Captain-general?

48
00:06:22,131 --> 00:06:24,467
Where...? Where are we?

49
00:06:25,885 --> 00:06:28,471
Still on course.

50
00:06:28,638 --> 00:06:33,017
You and your damned course.

51
00:06:33,685 --> 00:06:36,354
There is no Japans.

52
00:06:36,521 --> 00:06:40,066
But you... You will kill us all.

53
00:06:40,233 --> 00:06:43,444
We'll get there. We'll make landfall.

54
00:06:43,611 --> 00:06:48,700
It's a lie.
All lies from the beginning.

55
00:06:49,826 --> 00:06:52,745
God rot you, pilot.

56
00:06:52,912 --> 00:06:54,330
Reef!

57
00:06:54,497 --> 00:06:56,958
Reef ahead!

58
00:07:05,508 --> 00:07:08,177
All hands on deck!

59
00:07:08,344 --> 00:07:10,638
All hands on deck!

60
00:07:13,599 --> 00:07:17,520
We're lost! Lord Jesus help us!

61
00:07:19,522 --> 00:07:22,191
Get the crew on deck!

62
00:07:23,276 --> 00:07:25,278
Go on!

63
00:07:32,994 --> 00:07:36,039
Get out on deck! Out!

64
00:07:49,844 --> 00:07:51,804
[YELLS]

65
00:07:55,224 --> 00:07:58,561
Get aloft! The forecastle's ho!

66
00:08:02,565 --> 00:08:05,276
Aloft!

67
00:08:13,701 --> 00:08:15,328
[YELLS]

68
00:08:17,330 --> 00:08:19,207
Reef!

69
00:08:19,832 --> 00:08:23,086
Reef ahead!

70
00:08:32,762 --> 00:08:36,099
Turn, you whore from hell!

71
00:08:37,892 --> 00:08:40,144
Turn, damn you!

72
00:08:40,311 --> 00:08:42,772
Turn!

73
00:08:47,735 --> 00:08:49,904
[CRASHING]

74
00:10:36,093 --> 00:10:38,888
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

75
00:10:47,396 --> 00:10:48,773
Is this the Japans?

76
00:10:52,902 --> 00:10:54,028
The Japans?

77
00:11:18,177 --> 00:11:20,888
It is the Japans.
By God, it has to be.

78
00:12:09,812 --> 00:12:11,439
Sorry.

79
00:12:13,899 --> 00:12:15,526
Where are my boots?

80
00:12:20,114 --> 00:12:21,824
Boots.

81
00:12:24,201 --> 00:12:26,662
Feet. Boots.

82
00:13:19,006 --> 00:13:21,008
Thank you.

83
00:13:23,010 --> 00:13:25,554
My name John Blackthorne.

84
00:13:26,055 --> 00:13:27,932
What's your name?

85
00:13:30,351 --> 00:13:31,977
Blackthorne.

86
00:13:32,144 --> 00:13:33,646
What's your name?

87
00:13:37,733 --> 00:13:39,860
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

88
00:15:39,396 --> 00:15:44,693
Can you take me in your boat
to my ship?

89
00:15:47,446 --> 00:15:48,948
[SPEAKS IN JAPAN ESE]

90
00:16:49,466 --> 00:16:52,511
You wait here for me.

91
00:16:54,054 --> 00:16:55,889
Wait here for me.

92
00:16:56,056 --> 00:16:58,225
[SPEAKS IN JAPAN ESE]

93
00:17:23,167 --> 00:17:24,877
[SPEAKS IN JAPAN ESE]

94
00:17:25,044 --> 00:17:26,712
But this is my ship.

95
00:17:32,509 --> 00:17:35,471
There are papers in my cabin.

96
00:17:35,638 --> 00:17:37,765
I need them.

97
00:17:38,390 --> 00:17:40,059
[SPEAKS IN JAPAN ESE]

98
00:17:44,063 --> 00:17:49,485
I, me, want to go in there.

99
00:18:22,518 --> 00:18:25,688
SEBASTIO: Who are you?
- Who are you?

100
00:18:26,146 --> 00:18:28,524
I am Father Sebastio.

101
00:18:28,691 --> 00:18:31,318
And you are a heretic
Dutchman pirate.

102
00:18:31,485 --> 00:18:33,195
How did you get here?

103
00:18:33,404 --> 00:18:36,073
We were blown ashore.

104
00:18:36,240 --> 00:18:39,451
- What is this place? The Japans?
- Yes.

105
00:18:39,618 --> 00:18:42,204
The authorities know about you.

106
00:18:42,371 --> 00:18:45,582
They crucify criminals
and pirates here.

107
00:18:45,749 --> 00:18:47,167
You're going to die.

108
00:18:47,334 --> 00:18:50,546
- Where's my crew?
- They will die with you.

109
00:18:50,713 --> 00:18:53,799
May God burn you in hellfire
for all eternity.

110
00:18:58,387 --> 00:19:01,849
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

111
00:19:04,727 --> 00:19:06,311
[MAN SPEAKS IN JAPANESE]

112
00:19:21,910 --> 00:19:24,121
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

113
00:19:26,498 --> 00:19:28,667
Kasigi Omi-san wants to know
where do you come from?

114
00:19:28,834 --> 00:19:30,461
What's your nationality?

115
00:19:30,627 --> 00:19:33,922
- Who is he?
- The samurai in charge of this village.

116
00:19:34,089 --> 00:19:36,633
You'd better answer quickly.

117
00:19:36,800 --> 00:19:42,598
Tell him I'm English. I'm pilot-major
of the Erasmus out of Rotterdam.

118
00:19:42,806 --> 00:19:44,683
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

119
00:19:58,447 --> 00:20:03,243
Omi-san says you may walk around
the village until his master comes back.

120
00:20:03,410 --> 00:20:06,663
Lord Kasigi Yabu
will decide your fate.

121
00:20:06,830 --> 00:20:09,082
What about my crew?

122
00:20:09,249 --> 00:20:11,543
Where are they?

123
00:20:21,762 --> 00:20:24,056
Omi-san says,
"Do you understand?"

124
00:20:26,058 --> 00:20:28,769
What's "yes" in Japanese?

125
00:20:28,936 --> 00:20:30,145
[SPEAKS IN JAPAN ESE]

126
00:20:57,840 --> 00:21:00,884
[SEBASTIO SPEAKS IN LATIN]

127
00:22:23,884 --> 00:22:25,469
[GUARD SPEAKS IN JAPANESE]

128
00:22:43,070 --> 00:22:45,781
By the Lord Jesus, pilot,
you're alive.

129
00:22:45,948 --> 00:22:47,908
Where's the ship? ls she safe?

130
00:22:48,075 --> 00:22:51,620
Anchored in the bay.
Where are the others?

131
00:22:51,787 --> 00:22:55,999
Dead, pilot.
The savages took them away.

132
00:22:58,377 --> 00:23:00,128
[MOANING]

133
00:23:02,464 --> 00:23:03,840
Captain-general?

134
00:23:04,007 --> 00:23:07,094
He can't hear you.
All he does is lie there and moan.

135
00:23:07,469 --> 00:23:10,430
He's in God's hands. We all are.

136
00:23:10,597 --> 00:23:14,601
- Is it the Japans, pilot? ls it'?
- Aye, it is.

137
00:23:17,270 --> 00:23:20,190
But there's a priest here. A Jesuit.

138
00:23:20,357 --> 00:23:23,568
Where there be one priest,
there's bound to be others.

139
00:23:23,735 --> 00:23:27,698
Priests and papists...
They'll burn us at the stake.

140
00:23:28,281 --> 00:23:31,159
The Day of Judgment approaches.
We never should've sailed here.

141
00:23:31,326 --> 00:23:34,621
Are there riches, pilot?
ls there gold?

142
00:23:34,788 --> 00:23:38,000
- There must be. Gold and riches--
- Did you see it?

143
00:23:38,166 --> 00:23:40,460
- Have you seen the gold?
- No.

144
00:23:40,627 --> 00:23:44,131
Maybe Roper's right. Maybe it's
only greed that brought us here.

145
00:23:44,297 --> 00:23:46,133
- It's God's punishment--
- Stop it.

146
00:23:47,092 --> 00:23:51,054
We're the first ones to reach Japans,
and we'll be rich if we keep our wits.

147
00:23:51,221 --> 00:23:54,099
How? By trading with the devil?

148
00:23:54,266 --> 00:23:56,268
It's always the devil with you,
isn't it, Jan Roper?

149
00:23:56,435 --> 00:23:57,477
[CHUCKLES]

150
00:23:57,644 --> 00:23:59,396
The devil lives on your lips.

151
00:23:59,563 --> 00:24:02,399
Look to your soul, Johann Vinck.

152
00:24:02,566 --> 00:24:06,111
Will they let us back on the ship?
Will they let us go now?

153
00:24:07,029 --> 00:24:09,906
- The ship is under guard.
- Guards?

154
00:24:10,073 --> 00:24:12,951
Are the heathens aboard?
What are we to do?

155
00:24:13,118 --> 00:24:15,245
We must get away from here.
This is the land of Satan.

156
00:24:15,412 --> 00:24:17,998
Hold your tongue.
We'll do whatever we can.

157
00:24:19,207 --> 00:24:22,669
Their chief is coming soon.
Then we'll settle everything.

158
00:24:22,836 --> 00:24:25,213
Do you think he'll let us go?

159
00:24:26,048 --> 00:24:30,260
Why shouldn't he?
We've done them no harm.

160
00:24:30,427 --> 00:24:33,138
Look at the way
they all smile and bow.

161
00:24:33,305 --> 00:24:36,224
They're not bloodthirsty heathens,
are they, pilot?

162
00:24:45,859 --> 00:24:47,694
Are they?

163
00:25:43,667 --> 00:25:46,586
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

164
00:26:01,560 --> 00:26:03,311
<i>Hmm.</i>

165
00:26:03,979 --> 00:26:05,480
[CHUCKLES]

166
00:26:11,153 --> 00:26:14,447
- It's the same swill as before.
- Raw fish.

167
00:26:14,614 --> 00:26:16,825
How do they expect us to cook it
with no fire?

168
00:26:16,992 --> 00:26:19,494
[MAN SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

169
00:26:24,708 --> 00:26:27,919
- He wants you, pilot.
- Maybe the chief is here.

170
00:26:28,086 --> 00:26:32,799
- Tell him we come in peace.
- I'll do what I can.

171
00:26:35,844 --> 00:26:39,181
- He wants all of us.
- I'm not going with that devil.

172
00:26:39,347 --> 00:26:42,184
Roper, you and Pieterzoon,
bring the captain-general.

173
00:26:42,350 --> 00:26:44,686
- He's dying. Let the poor man lie.
- Do as I say.

174
00:26:44,853 --> 00:26:46,521
I'll bring him, pilot.

175
00:26:54,571 --> 00:26:56,239
[GRUNTS]

176
00:27:23,308 --> 00:27:26,228
- Bow to him.
- He's a heathen savage.

177
00:27:26,394 --> 00:27:27,771
[MAN SHOUTS IN JAPANESE]

178
00:27:27,938 --> 00:27:30,232
[ALL GRUNTING]

179
00:27:46,831 --> 00:27:53,129
The daimyo, Kasigi Yabu, Lord of lzu,
wants to know how you got here.

180
00:27:53,296 --> 00:27:56,466
- By Magellan's Pass.
- Liar.

181
00:27:56,633 --> 00:28:01,680
Magellan's Pass is secret.
You came by Africa and India.

182
00:28:01,846 --> 00:28:04,307
The pass was secret.

183
00:28:04,474 --> 00:28:08,353
A Portuguese sold us a rutter,
a pilot's chart book from his ship.

184
00:28:08,520 --> 00:28:09,646
Liar.

185
00:28:11,898 --> 00:28:14,734
Soon all our ships will know the way
through to the Pacific.

186
00:28:14,901 --> 00:28:16,820
Heretic lies.

187
00:28:17,654 --> 00:28:22,075
But you'll tell the truth soon enough.
They use torture here.

188
00:28:38,300 --> 00:28:42,387
Lord Kasigi Yabu asks what acts
of piracy you have committed.

189
00:28:42,762 --> 00:28:46,683
None. We are not pirates,
we come in peace.

190
00:28:46,933 --> 00:28:50,103
- Another lie.
- Give him my answer, damn you.

191
00:28:50,895 --> 00:28:56,860
- God curse you forever.
- Tell him we're not pirates, Jesuit pig.

192
00:29:09,247 --> 00:29:10,665
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

193
00:29:27,974 --> 00:29:33,146
Lord Kasigi Yabu says
your pirate ship is confiscated.

194
00:29:33,813 --> 00:29:37,108
You papist liar. You lied to him.

195
00:29:40,236 --> 00:29:41,946
You filthy lying Jesuit.

196
00:30:12,894 --> 00:30:16,689
- God. Sweet Jesus' death.
- We should all pray.

197
00:30:16,856 --> 00:30:19,192
- Vinck just did.
- I'm sick.

198
00:30:19,359 --> 00:30:21,903
- I've got to lie down.
- Don't touch the captain-general.

199
00:30:22,112 --> 00:30:25,240
- He's dying anyway.
- I said you don't touch him!

200
00:30:25,407 --> 00:30:28,660
Shut up! All of you, shut up!

201
00:30:30,120 --> 00:30:35,500
- Get off my foot.
- Are they going to kill us, pilot?

202
00:31:06,281 --> 00:31:09,742
[ALL YELLING]

203
00:31:23,256 --> 00:31:27,719
Lord Kasigi Yabu has graciously
spared all your lives.

204
00:31:28,136 --> 00:31:30,180
All except one.

205
00:31:30,346 --> 00:31:35,852
One of you is to die.
You are to choose who it will be.

206
00:31:36,019 --> 00:31:41,858
But you, pilot,
you are not to be the one chosen.

207
00:31:51,159 --> 00:31:53,828
Lord Jesus help us.

208
00:32:25,527 --> 00:32:30,114
- What are we to do now, pilot?
- I don't know.

209
00:32:30,281 --> 00:32:34,827
How?
How are we to choose someone?

210
00:32:34,994 --> 00:32:37,413
We don't. We fight them.

211
00:32:37,580 --> 00:32:39,415
With What?

212
00:32:39,582 --> 00:32:42,877
Give them the captain-general,
he's useless anyway.

213
00:32:43,044 --> 00:32:47,048
- You make a man sick--
- They'll take none of us without a fight.

214
00:32:47,215 --> 00:32:50,885
If we fight, they'll kill us all.
You heard what he said.

215
00:32:51,052 --> 00:32:55,890
All our lives are spared except one.
How do we choose?

216
00:32:56,057 --> 00:32:57,433
We don't, damn it.

217
00:33:00,311 --> 00:33:02,063
Pilot,

218
00:33:02,564 --> 00:33:05,525
this doesn't concern you
anymore.

219
00:33:05,692 --> 00:33:10,488
It's between us now.
It's our decision.

220
00:33:10,655 --> 00:33:12,657
Aye.

221
00:33:12,824 --> 00:33:18,204
We'll draw lots. Straws.
One shorter than the rest. Agreed?

222
00:33:18,371 --> 00:33:21,541
What about the captain-general?
He wasn't excluded.

223
00:33:21,708 --> 00:33:27,505
- Then let the last straw be for him.
- Who'll be the first to pick?

224
00:33:27,672 --> 00:33:34,387
How do we know that the man who
picks the short straw will go? Huh?

225
00:33:34,554 --> 00:33:37,140
How do we know that?

226
00:33:37,307 --> 00:33:39,392
We'll all swear to God.

227
00:33:39,559 --> 00:33:43,021
A holy vow. I swear it.

228
00:33:43,187 --> 00:33:46,816
- I swear.
- I swear it.

229
00:33:46,983 --> 00:33:48,985
I swear to God.

230
00:34:01,039 --> 00:34:02,999
God be praised.

231
00:34:39,243 --> 00:34:40,536
[GASPS]

232
00:35:49,605 --> 00:35:51,399
[MAN SPEAKS IN JAPANESE]

233
00:36:03,077 --> 00:36:05,329
- Not without a fight.
- But we agreed.

234
00:36:05,496 --> 00:36:06,914
I didn't.

235
00:36:07,081 --> 00:36:09,584
It's all right, pilot.

236
00:36:09,751 --> 00:36:14,005
We agreed. It was fair.
It's God's will.

237
00:36:14,172 --> 00:36:18,843
- Nobody is going without a fight.
MAETSUKKER: You'll get us all killed.

238
00:36:30,438 --> 00:36:32,690
BLACKTHORNE:
Help me! Come on! For your lives!

239
00:36:34,525 --> 00:36:36,527
[YELLING AND GRUNTING]

240
00:37:12,271 --> 00:37:15,483
No! No, it's not me!
I'm not the one to go!

241
00:37:16,818 --> 00:37:19,654
Help me! For God's sake!

242
00:37:55,857 --> 00:37:58,192
I was going.

243
00:37:58,359 --> 00:38:01,362
I swear before Christ, I was going.

244
