484
01:05:45,733 --> 01:05:47,985
why don't you take a look
at the ship?

485
01:05:49,987 --> 01:05:52,281
- Where are they, <i>inglés?</i>
- What?

486
01:05:52,448 --> 01:05:55,159
Your charts. You've hidden them.

487
01:05:55,326 --> 01:06:00,039
That's why you came onboard.
No pilot would worry about clothes.

488
01:06:00,206 --> 01:06:04,126
You came for your rutters.
You want me out so you can get them.

489
01:06:05,294 --> 01:06:07,797
You're right,
that's why I wanted to come.

490
01:06:07,964 --> 01:06:09,840
But they were in here.

491
01:06:10,049 --> 01:06:14,971
Oh, I don't want to steal them.
I just want to copy a part or two.

492
01:06:15,137 --> 01:06:20,393
- They were in the sea chest.
- Liar. Come on, there's no time.

493
01:06:20,560 --> 01:06:24,272
I took your word,
now you take mine, pilot to pilot.

494
01:06:24,772 --> 01:06:26,899
I won't steal them.

495
01:06:43,874 --> 01:06:45,835
Damn!

496
01:06:46,002 --> 01:06:47,920
Stolen.

497
01:06:49,046 --> 01:06:50,965
What?

498
01:06:58,097 --> 01:07:00,725
<i>Do</i> I <i>believe you, inglés?</i>

499
01:07:01,726 --> 01:07:05,021
Eh, I think so.
This was where you kept them?

500
01:07:05,187 --> 01:07:07,440
- Yes.
- Everything?

501
01:07:07,607 --> 01:07:13,029
Even your Portuguese rutter? Ha, ha.
Come on, it had to be Portuguese.

502
01:07:13,195 --> 01:07:16,616
- How else would you have got here?
- Yes, even the Portuguese rutter.

503
01:07:16,782 --> 01:07:18,451
That's gone too.

504
01:07:19,410 --> 01:07:23,122
Halfway around the Earth
and no way to get home.

505
01:07:23,289 --> 01:07:25,916
Lord give me strength!

506
01:07:31,589 --> 01:07:34,091
I know what you feel, inglés.

507
01:07:34,925 --> 01:07:37,261
I feel sorry for you.

508
01:07:37,428 --> 01:07:39,639
It happened to me once.

509
01:07:39,805 --> 01:07:42,642
<i>He was inglés too, the Mei.</i>

510
01:07:42,808 --> 01:07:47,355
Heh. May his ship drown
and he burn in hell forever.

511
01:07:49,565 --> 01:07:53,277
Come on, let's get back to my ship.

512
01:08:07,291 --> 01:08:10,586
[DRUM BEATING
AND MEN CHANTING]

513
01:08:18,678 --> 01:08:21,889
You never saw a slaver
move like this.

514
01:08:22,056 --> 01:08:26,519
Even with an infidel Turk
whipping them to a lather.

515
01:08:26,686 --> 01:08:29,105
Those are samurai rowers.

516
01:08:29,271 --> 01:08:32,650
They'll stroke till they die,
if Lord Toranaga wishes.

517
01:08:32,817 --> 01:08:34,568
How far is this place
you're taking me?

518
01:08:34,735 --> 01:08:37,113
Osaka? Oh.

519
01:08:37,279 --> 01:08:38,906
Three hundred-odd sea miles,

520
01:08:39,073 --> 01:08:41,701
and we'll be there
in less than 4O hours.

521
01:08:41,867 --> 01:08:44,495
Hey, Captain-san.

522
01:08:45,162 --> 01:08:46,956
[RODRIGUES SPEAKS
IN JAPANESE]

523
01:08:48,666 --> 01:08:50,543
West-southwest.

524
01:08:50,710 --> 01:08:51,877
[CHUCKLES]

525
01:08:52,044 --> 01:08:55,381
I guess you know your compass,
inglés.

526
01:08:55,548 --> 01:08:57,883
These galleys normally
hug the coast for safety,

527
01:08:58,050 --> 01:09:01,595
but that would take too much time,
and time is important.

528
01:09:01,804 --> 01:09:05,683
Toranaga asked me to pilot Toda
to Anjiro and back quickly.

529
01:09:05,850 --> 01:09:09,311
- I get a bonus if we're on time.
- You work for Toranaga?

530
01:09:09,478 --> 01:09:12,189
Me work for him? Hell, no.

531
01:09:12,356 --> 01:09:16,902
I was just visiting Osaka, my captain
and me. This was just a favor.

532
01:09:18,571 --> 01:09:21,615
They're not great ocean sailors,
the Jap men.

533
01:09:22,575 --> 01:09:25,953
Great pirates and fighters
and coastal sailors,

534
01:09:26,120 --> 01:09:28,164
but the deep frightens them.

535
01:09:34,754 --> 01:09:38,591
- What are they going to do with me?
- Whatever they want to do.

536
01:09:40,509 --> 01:09:43,387
- What's your own ship like?
- Oh, heh.

537
01:09:43,554 --> 01:09:45,598
I'm the pilot of...

538
01:09:48,350 --> 01:09:52,313
I keep forgetting
that you're the enemy, inglés.

539
01:09:53,105 --> 01:09:57,985
- We've been allies for centuries.
- But we're not now.

540
01:09:59,487 --> 01:10:04,241
Go below, inglés. Get some rest.
If you want to sleep, use my cabin.

541
01:10:04,992 --> 01:10:07,411
You're tired and so am I.

542
01:10:08,704 --> 01:10:10,748
Tired men make mistakes.

543
01:11:01,841 --> 01:11:03,425
[SIGHS]

544
01:11:27,867 --> 01:11:31,287
- How do you feel, <i>inglés?</i>
- Rested.

545
01:11:33,455 --> 01:11:35,875
- What do you think?
- I think there'll be a storm.

546
01:11:36,041 --> 01:11:37,376
- When?
- Before the day's out.

547
01:11:37,543 --> 01:11:41,297
Ha, ha. Now, that is a safe guess.

548
01:11:42,506 --> 01:11:45,134
If this were your ship,
what would you do?

549
01:11:45,301 --> 01:11:46,802
How far is the nearest land?

550
01:11:47,011 --> 01:11:50,931
Oh. Three, maybe four hours.

551
01:11:51,098 --> 01:11:53,934
If we run for cover,
it'll cost me my bonus.

552
01:11:55,936 --> 01:12:00,024
Oh, Madonna. I'm a tired man.

553
01:12:00,190 --> 01:12:02,026
Then go sleep,
I'll take the watch for you.

554
01:12:03,110 --> 01:12:05,070
If the wind changes,
I'll wake you.

555
01:12:05,237 --> 01:12:06,322
[RODRIGUES CHUCKLES]

556
01:12:06,488 --> 01:12:10,367
All right, inglés. I think I'll trust you.
God knows why.

557
01:12:11,577 --> 01:12:14,455
Maintain this course. At the next turn,
go four degrees more westerly,

558
01:12:14,622 --> 01:12:17,541
and at the next, six more westerly.

559
01:12:18,208 --> 01:12:19,293
[SPEAKS IN JAPAN ESE]

560
01:12:19,501 --> 01:12:20,669
Ha, ha, hai.

561
01:12:20,836 --> 01:12:25,841
Four degrees westerly it is.
Go below. Your bunk's comfortable.

562
01:12:55,496 --> 01:12:59,291
Ah, priest, what have you given me?

563
01:13:02,753 --> 01:13:06,298
God curse me and my lack of wits.

564
01:13:09,802 --> 01:13:11,887
[WIND WHISTLING]

565
01:13:51,760 --> 01:13:55,973
There's a storm there, all right.
This craft won't take much water.

566
01:13:58,350 --> 01:14:01,645
- How was your sleep?
- Short.

567
01:14:01,812 --> 01:14:04,982
But more than I would've had
if you weren't here.

568
01:14:08,068 --> 01:14:10,946
- It can't be tai-fun.
- What?

569
01:14:11,113 --> 01:14:15,034
Tai-fun, huge winds.
Worst storms you've ever seen.

570
01:14:15,868 --> 01:14:19,413
- We're not in the tai-fun season.
- When's that?

571
01:14:19,580 --> 01:14:20,622
[CHUCKLES]

572
01:14:20,789 --> 01:14:23,751
It's not now, enemy.

573
01:14:27,713 --> 01:14:33,052
It looks rotten enough.
I'll take your advice and head for land.

574
01:14:33,218 --> 01:14:36,096
- Steer north by west.
- North by west, aye.

575
01:14:36,263 --> 01:14:38,432
Hey, Captain-san.

576
01:14:41,727 --> 01:14:44,438
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

577
01:14:45,397 --> 01:14:47,107
[SPEAKS IN JAPAN ESE]

578
01:14:47,524 --> 01:14:50,069
[DRUMBEAT AND CHANTING
QUICKEN]

579
01:14:54,239 --> 01:14:56,533
What's that, <i>isogi?</i>
"Hurry up"?

580
01:14:56,700 --> 01:15:01,914
Ha, ha. There's no harm
in you learning a little Jap man talk.

581
01:15:02,456 --> 01:15:06,168
You need about ten words
and then you can make them dance.

582
01:15:06,335 --> 01:15:11,090
That's if they're the right words.
And if they're in the mood.

583
01:15:11,256 --> 01:15:14,301
[BOTH SPEAK IN JAPANESE]

584
01:15:15,344 --> 01:15:17,429
<i>Hey, inglés,</i>

585
01:15:18,305 --> 01:15:21,308
maybe you learn too damn fast.

586
01:15:27,481 --> 01:15:29,817
[WIND HOWLING]

587
01:15:40,160 --> 01:15:42,204
[THUNDER CRASHING]

588
01:16:04,977 --> 01:16:09,314
Go forward. Get them to start bailing.
Make them understand.

589
01:16:09,481 --> 01:16:11,483
Hurry. Hurry.

590
01:16:17,573 --> 01:16:20,492
Ship oars! Stop rowing!

591
01:16:20,993 --> 01:16:22,870
[SPEAKS IN JAPAN ESE]

592
01:16:23,036 --> 01:16:24,163
Stop rowing!

593
01:16:52,191 --> 01:16:56,695
- What do you think, <i>inglés?</i>
- You'll do what you want.

594
01:16:56,862 --> 01:17:01,950
But she won't take much water.
We'll go down like a stone.

595
01:17:03,160 --> 01:17:07,497
Next time I go forward,
tell me you're putting her into the wind.

596
01:17:07,664 --> 01:17:10,292
Ah, that was the hand of God,
inglés.

597
01:17:10,459 --> 01:17:13,879
A wave slapped her rump around.

598
01:17:14,880 --> 01:17:17,090
We'll keep her into the wind.

599
01:17:17,257 --> 01:17:20,969
When the time's right,
we'll make a stab for the shore.

600
01:17:21,803 --> 01:17:26,683
My nose tells me
if we turn and run, we'll flounder.

601
01:17:26,850 --> 01:17:29,436
If we don't turn, we'll never make it.

602
01:17:29,603 --> 01:17:31,980
For God's sake, what would you do?

603
01:17:32,147 --> 01:17:34,733
Wait till we're past the headland,

604
01:17:34,900 --> 01:17:38,528
fall off from the wind and make
the rowers pull for their lives.

605
01:17:39,655 --> 01:17:42,157
- That's dangerous.
- I know.

606
01:17:47,079 --> 01:17:48,705
All right.

607
01:17:49,831 --> 01:17:52,918
I'll go forward,
you take the helm.

608
01:17:53,085 --> 01:17:58,090
Watch me, and when I signal,
go west-northwest for the shore.

609
01:17:58,257 --> 01:18:01,593
- Watch me very closely.
- I will.

610
01:18:09,059 --> 01:18:10,352
Hey.

611
01:18:11,812 --> 01:18:14,398
You'll watch for my order,
and obey my orders.

612
01:18:14,564 --> 01:18:17,442
Do you want me
to take the helm or not'?

613
01:18:18,235 --> 01:18:21,613
I have to trust you again, inglés.

614
01:18:21,780 --> 01:18:24,574
And I hate trusting you.

615
01:18:33,542 --> 01:18:35,961
Steady as she goes.

616
01:18:48,974 --> 01:18:52,811
Hard aport...now!

617
01:18:52,978 --> 01:18:55,856
Hard aport, aye!

618
01:18:57,107 --> 01:18:59,735
Pull, you buggers.

619
01:18:59,901 --> 01:19:03,322
One, two, one, two.

620
01:19:03,488 --> 01:19:06,992
One, two, one, two.

621
01:19:07,159 --> 01:19:08,910
One, two-- Aah!

622
01:19:11,455 --> 01:19:14,082
Damn you, Rodrigues!

623
01:19:14,249 --> 01:19:15,375
[DRUMBEAT AND
CHANTING STOP]

624
01:20:49,553 --> 01:20:51,263
Rodrigues.

625
01:20:53,557 --> 01:20:55,058
Rodrigues.

626
01:21:08,155 --> 01:21:09,281
Yabu-san.

627
01:21:09,948 --> 01:21:13,952
Thank you for saving his life.
Thank you for your courage.

628
01:21:14,119 --> 01:21:17,247
Thank you,
you black-eyed son of a whore.

629
01:22:00,290 --> 01:22:02,250
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

630
01:22:19,100 --> 01:22:21,686
You may come up one by one.

631
01:22:21,853 --> 01:22:24,981
You may live
in the world of men again.

632
01:22:25,148 --> 01:22:28,360
But break any rule,
and you'll be put back.

633
01:22:28,527 --> 01:22:31,696
What about the pilot?
What's happened to him?

634
01:22:31,863 --> 01:22:34,616
If you don't come out now,
you will stay down there.

635
01:23:07,148 --> 01:23:11,069
- Where's the other man?
- Captain-General Spillbergen's dead.

636
01:23:11,236 --> 01:23:13,029
God rest his soul.

637
01:23:13,196 --> 01:23:15,907
He's down there lying in the filth.

638
01:23:27,168 --> 01:23:28,795
Omi-san wants you to bow to him.

639
01:23:40,098 --> 01:23:43,101
He wants us to come. Come on.

640
01:24:33,943 --> 01:24:35,779
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

641
01:25:49,811 --> 01:25:51,563
[GRUNTING]

642
01:27:00,340 --> 01:27:03,802
So now I owe you a life, inglés.

643
01:27:03,968 --> 01:27:05,011
[RODRIGUES CHUCKLES]

644
01:27:05,178 --> 01:27:06,763
Oh!

645
01:27:06,930 --> 01:27:09,015
God curse you.

646
01:27:09,182 --> 01:27:13,353
It was Kasigi Yabu who saved
your miserable body. Curse him.

647
01:27:13,520 --> 01:27:19,108
No. Those Jappos would never have
come after me if it weren't for you.

648
01:27:19,859 --> 01:27:21,778
The curse is thine.

649
01:27:27,075 --> 01:27:28,868
There's a bottle of grog over there.

650
01:27:43,424 --> 01:27:44,926
Here.

651
01:27:48,513 --> 01:27:51,307
You make a foul nurse, inglés.

652
01:27:51,474 --> 01:27:53,685
It's your black heart.

653
01:27:59,107 --> 01:28:01,526
Bring the bottle over here.

654
01:28:06,364 --> 01:28:08,658
- How do you feel?
- Better.

655
01:28:08,825 --> 01:28:13,705
Considering my head's on fire
and my mouth tastes of pigswill.

656
01:28:13,913 --> 01:28:15,206
Eh-eh-eh.

657
01:28:15,373 --> 01:28:17,333
Just give me the bottle.

658
01:28:21,671 --> 01:28:25,216
This, uh, Toranaga,

659
01:28:25,717 --> 01:28:29,429
- why does he want to see me?
- I don't know.

660
01:28:29,888 --> 01:28:32,348
By the Blessed Virgin,
I don't know.

661
01:28:32,515 --> 01:28:35,894
And since I owe you something,
here's some truth in part payment.

662
01:28:37,437 --> 01:28:42,191
Never forget the Jap men
are six-faced and have three hearts.

663
01:28:42,358 --> 01:28:45,904
So be careful, inglés.
Be careful what you say.

664
01:28:46,070 --> 01:28:51,159
Be careful how you move.
Even be careful how you think.

665
01:28:51,534 --> 01:28:53,995
Especially with Toranaga.

666
01:28:54,412 --> 01:28:56,414
Toranaga...

667
01:28:57,540 --> 01:28:59,208
What's he like?

668
01:29:01,377 --> 01:29:05,006
Same as the rest of them.
Only worse.

669
01:29:06,090 --> 01:29:10,386
They had 600 years
of civil war in this country,

670
01:29:10,553 --> 01:29:16,476
until about 35 years ago
when Goroda conquered half of Japan

671
01:29:16,643 --> 01:29:19,479
and made himself
ichi-ban lord of the country.

672
01:29:19,646 --> 01:29:22,607
Know who helped him? Toranaga.

673
01:29:22,774 --> 01:29:27,278
Then, I guess it was 16 years ago,

674
01:29:28,780 --> 01:29:34,619
one of his own generals killed Goroda
and another stepped into his sandals.

675
01:29:35,119 --> 01:29:37,664
General Nakamura.

676
01:29:37,830 --> 01:29:39,749
Know who helped him?

677
01:29:39,916 --> 01:29:43,294
- Toranaga.
- Right, inglés. Toranaga.

678
01:29:43,461 --> 01:29:47,173
Another big monkey-sama, lshido.

679
01:29:48,091 --> 01:29:51,761
Toranaga in the east,
lshido in the west.

680
01:29:52,971 --> 01:29:57,308
Sooner or later
there'll be another bloody civil war.

681
01:30:34,971 --> 01:30:36,889
[RODRIGUES GROANS]

682
01:30:38,975 --> 01:30:42,520
Madonna,
I think I got drunk last night.

683
01:30:43,271 --> 01:30:45,982
- Where are we?
- On course, pilot.

684
01:30:46,649 --> 01:30:49,819
You're the pilot now. Ha, ha-- Ooh.

685
01:30:51,195 --> 01:30:54,198
A person could think
that was funny.

686
01:30:54,365 --> 01:30:59,328
You're supposed to be the prisoner.
You could be taking us anywhere.

687
01:30:59,495 --> 01:31:02,540
But you, you wouldn't do that.

688
01:31:04,000 --> 01:31:05,918
If they were taking me
to lshido's castle,

689
01:31:06,085 --> 01:31:08,212
I wouldn't sail them there.

690
01:31:08,379 --> 01:31:11,549
Ishido? I thought they were
taking me to Toranaga.

691
01:31:11,716 --> 01:31:16,220
So they are. Except that
Toranaga's in Osaka Castle,

692
01:31:16,387 --> 01:31:21,684
and Osaka Castle belongs to lshido.
And what a butcher he is.

693
01:31:21,851 --> 01:31:26,355
Hell, they all are. Everything
in this country's upside down.

694
01:31:28,441 --> 01:31:31,527
- What are you steering?
- South by southwest.

695
01:31:31,694 --> 01:31:33,237
How did you know?
Who told you?

696
01:31:33,404 --> 01:31:35,573
- You did.
- Me?

697
01:31:35,782 --> 01:31:37,075
[CHUCKLES]

698
01:31:37,241 --> 01:31:40,244
Madonna, it's all in a haze.

699
01:31:40,411 --> 01:31:42,580
You looked in my rutter!

700
01:31:42,914 --> 01:31:44,957
[BOTH LAUGHING]

701
01:31:47,126 --> 01:31:50,880
Ah, inglés, life is so strange.

702
01:31:52,256 --> 01:31:55,259
And if I live,
it is by the grace of God,

703
01:31:56,052 --> 01:32:00,681
helped by a heretic
and a Jap man.

704
01:32:01,599 --> 01:32:04,060
There's the sod-eating sama.

705
01:32:04,727 --> 01:32:06,437
I'd better go and thank him.

706
01:32:08,231 --> 01:32:11,484
You're a dangerous man, inglés.

707
01:32:11,984 --> 01:32:14,278
Maybe we'd all be better off
if they killed you.

708
01:32:41,889 --> 01:32:46,394
<i>NARRATOR". Osaka,
the white castle city of Lord lshido.</i>

709
01:33:02,118 --> 01:33:04,662
<i>An escort of 2O samurai
was on the dock,</i>

710
01:33:04,996 --> 01:33:09,292
<i>wearing the brown uniform
of Toranaga's army,</i>

711
01:33:11,335 --> 01:33:15,798
<i>under the command
of Toranaga's youngest son,</i>

712
01:33:15,965 --> 01:33:18,134
<i>Lord Naga.</i>

713
01:33:28,102 --> 01:33:30,229
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

714
01:33:57,215 --> 01:34:00,009
Now, inglés,
it's Toranaga's fifth son.

715
01:34:00,176 --> 01:34:02,803
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

716
01:34:05,598 --> 01:34:08,559
That should keep him happy.
Come on.

717
01:34:11,187 --> 01:34:13,314
Now what's the matter?

718
01:34:14,190 --> 01:34:16,150
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

719
01:34:19,987 --> 01:34:21,405
You're staying onboard, inglés.

720
01:34:22,823 --> 01:34:25,201
- Why?
- It wouldn't do any good to ask.

721
01:34:25,368 --> 01:34:27,954
When Toranaga's ready,
you'll find out.

722
01:34:35,628 --> 01:34:36,921
<i>Go with God, inglés.</i>

